**Component Import/Export Flow:**

**1. Export component:**
```jsx
// Navbar.jsx
const Navbar = () => {
  return <nav><h1>My Navbar</h1></nav>;
}

export default Navbar; // ‚Üê Export
```

**2. Import & use:**
```jsx
// App.jsx
import Navbar from './components/Navbar'; // ‚Üê Import

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Navbar /> {/* ‚Üê Use */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Rules:**
- Component names must start with **capital letter**
- Use `export default` for single component files
- Import path matches file location

**Props** = Data passed from parent ‚Üí child components

**Basic usage:**
```jsx
// Child component
const Hero = ({ title, subtitle }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{subtitle}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// Parent usage
<Hero title="Test Title" subtitle="This is a subtitle" />
```

**With defaults:**
```jsx
const Hero = ({ title = 'Default', subtitle = 'Default' }) => {
  // Uses defaults if props not provided
}
```

**Wrapping** = Putting content inside a component ‚Üí becomes `children`

**Pattern:**
```jsx
// Wrapper component
const Card = ({ children }) => {
  return (
    <div className="card-styles">
      {children}  {/* Content goes here */}
    </div>
  );
}

// Usage
<Card>
  <h1>Hello!</h1>
  <p>This gets the card styling</p>
</Card>
```

**Use case:** Reusable layout/styling containers

**Todo State Management:**

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

function App() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);     // All tasks
  const [newTodo, setNewTodo] = useState(''); // Current input

  return (
    <div>
      <input 
        value={newTodo} 
        onChange={(e) => setNewTodo(e.target.value)} 
      />
      {/* Todo list displays here */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**State roles:**
- `todos` = Basket of all tasks (array)
- `newTodo` = Task currently being typed (string)

**useEffect Dependency Array** = Controls when effect runs

```jsx
// Run once on mount
useEffect(() => {}, []);

// Run every render  
useEffect(() => {});

// Run when count changes
useEffect(() => {}, [count]);
```

**Why it matters:** Prevents unnecessary re-runs, keeps app fast
**Pattern:** List only variables that should trigger re-execution

**Loading from localStorage:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const todos = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < localStorage.length; i++) {
    const key = localStorage.key(i);
    if (key.startsWith('newTask')) {
      todos.push({
        key,                    // Unique ID
        text: localStorage.getItem(key),  // Task text
        completed: false        // Status tracking
      });
    }
  }
  setSavedTodos(todos);
}, []);
```

**Why objects instead of strings?**
- Track completion status
- Unique keys for identification
- Store multiple properties per task

**Add + save task:**
```jsx
const addTodo = () => {
  if (newTodo.trim() === '') return;

  // Generate unique key
  let i = 0;
  while (localStorage.getItem(`newTask${i}`) !== null) i++;
  const key = `newTask${i}`;

  localStorage.setItem(key, newTodo);
  setTodos([...todos, { key, text: newTodo, completed: false }]);
  setNewTodo('');
};
```

**Render tasks with actions:**
```jsx
{todos.map((task) => (
  <div key={task.key} className="task">
    <li style={{
      textDecoration: task.completed ? "line-through" : "none",
      color: task.completed ? "red" : "black"
    }}>
      {task.text}
    </li>
    <button onClick={() => toggleComplete(task.key)}>‚úì</button>
    <button onClick={() => deleteTask(task.key)}>üóëÔ∏è</button>
  </div>
))}
```

**Toggle completion:**
```jsx
const toggleComplete = (key) => {
  setTodos(
    todos.map((task) =>
      task.key === key ? { ...task, completed: !task.completed } : task
    )
  );
};
```

**What it does:** Flips `completed` boolean for the matching task

**Delete from both state and storage:**
```jsx
const deleteTask = (key) => {
  setTodos(todos.filter((task) => task.key !== key));  // Remove from state
  localStorage.removeItem(key);                        // Remove from storage
};
```

**Parent component:**
```jsx
const [showAddForm, setShowAddForm] = useState(false);

{showAddForm && <AddNewExpense closeForm={() => setShowAddForm(false)} />}
```

**Child component:**
```jsx
const AddNewExpense = ({ closeForm }) => {
  return <button onClick={closeForm}>Cancel</button>;
};
```

**Store today's date:**
```jsx
const [date, setDate] = useState(
  new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0]  // "2025-11-12"
);
```

**Breakdown:**
- `new Date()` ‚Üí current date
- `.toISOString()` ‚Üí "2025-11-12T14:00:00.000Z"  
- `.split('T')[0]` ‚Üí keep only date part

**Rendering** = Converting JSX ‚Üí HTML that browser displays

**Examples:**
```jsx
// Simple render
function App() { return <h1>Hello!</h1>; }

// Conditional render
{isLoggedIn ? <p>Welcome</p> : <p>Login</p>}

// State-triggered re-render
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
<button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Click {count}</button>
```

**Key point:** React updates DOM when state/props change

**Problem:** Objects don't have numeric indices

**‚ùå Wrong:**
```jsx
const style = { color: 'red', bg: 'orange' };
style[1] // undefined
```

**‚úÖ Solutions:**
```jsx
// Access by key
const style = { normal: { color: 'red' }, active: { color: 'blue' } };
<button style={style.active}>Click</button>

// Or use array
const styles = [{ color: 'red' }, { color: 'blue' }];
<button style={styles[1]}>Click</button>
```

**Key point:** Objects use keys, arrays use indices

**Expense Date Filtering** = Compare dates using getFullYear/getMonth/getDate

**React Pattern:**
```js
useEffect(() => {
  const today = new Date();
  const totals = { today: 0, month: 0, year: 0 };

  expenses.forEach(({ amount, date }) => {
    const expDate = new Date(date);

    // Year ‚Üí Month ‚Üí Day nested checks
    if (expDate.getFullYear() === today.getFullYear()) {
      totals.year += amount;

      if (expDate.getMonth() === today.getMonth()) {
        totals.month += amount;

        if (expDate.getDate() === today.getDate()) {
          totals.today += amount;
        }
      }
    }
  });

  setTotals(totals);
}, [expenses]);
```

**Logic flow:** Year check ‚Üí Month check ‚Üí Day check (efficient nesting)

**Date Comparison** = Use Date methods for year/month/day checks

```js
const today = new Date();
const otherDate = new Date(someDate);

const sameYear = otherDate.getFullYear() === today.getFullYear();
const sameMonth = otherDate.getMonth() === today.getMonth();
const sameDay = otherDate.getDate() === today.getDate();
```

**Efficient nested checking:**
```js
if (sameYear) {
  // Year logic
  if (sameMonth) {
    // Month logic  
    if (sameDay) {
      // Day logic
    }
  }
}
```

**Methods:** getFullYear(), getMonth() (0-11), getDate() (1-31)

**Custom Hooks** = Reusable functions that contain React hook logic

**Rules:**
- Name starts with `use` (useCounter, useFetch)
- Can use any built-in hooks
- Returns data/functions, NOT JSX

**Example:**
```jsx
// Custom hook
function useCounter(initial = 0) {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(initial)
  return [count, setCount]
}

// Usage in component
const [count, setCount] = useCounter(0)
```

**Benefits:** Logic reuse, cleaner components, extract complex effects

**Object.entries()** = Convert object to [key, value] pairs

**Basic usage:**
```js
Object.entries({ a: 1, b: 2 })
// ‚Üí [['a', 1], ['b', 2]]
```

**With destructuring:**
```js
Object.entries(obj).map(([key, value]) => {
  // key = 'a', value = 1
})
```

**Nested destructuring:**
```js
Object.entries(obj).map(([category, { expenses, total }]) => {
  // category = key
  // expenses, total = nested properties
})
```

**Use case:** Loop through objects in React rendering

**Cascading Renders** = Infinite re-render loop

**Cause:**
```
render ‚Üí useEffect ‚Üí setState ‚Üí render ‚Üí useEffect ‚Üí ...
```

**‚ùå Problem pattern:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  setState(data) // Triggers re-render
}, [state]) // state in dependencies
```

**‚úÖ Solution:** Define async functions inside useEffect
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    const res = await fetch(url)
    setData(await res.json())
  }
  fetchData()
}, []) // Empty dependencies
```

**Fix:** Avoid state setters in dependency arrays

**Safe Data Fetching Pattern:**

**1. State setup:**
```jsx
const [data, setData] = useState(null)
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true)
```

**2. Async function:**
```jsx
const fetchData = async () => {
  try {
    setLoading(true)
    const res = await fetch('API_URL')
    setData(await res.json())
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err)
  } finally {
    setLoading(false)
  }
}
```

**3. Call in useEffect:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => { fetchData() }, [])
```

**4. Render:**
```jsx
{loading ? <p>Loading...</p> : <p>{data?.name}</p>}
```

**Best practices:** try/catch, finally, optional chaining

**JavaScript Dates:**

**new Date()** - Creates readable date object:
```js
const now = new Date();                    // Current date/time
const birthday = new Date('2025-11-03');  // Specific date

// Extract parts:
const month = now.getMonth() + 1; // 0-indexed
const day = now.getDate();
const year = now.getFullYear();
```

**Date.now()** - Milliseconds since 1970 (Unix epoch):
```js
const timestamp = Date.now(); // 1731474081650

// Measure time:
const start = Date.now();
// ... do work
const elapsed = Date.now() - start;
```

**Summary:**
- `new Date()` ‚Üí Human-readable dates
- `Date.now()` ‚Üí Fast timestamps for calculations

**Event Propagation** = How events travel through DOM

**Three phases:**
1. **Capturing**: Window ‚Üí target (trickle down)
2. **Target**: Reaches clicked element  
3. **Bubbling**: Target ‚Üí window (bubble up) ‚Üê **default**

**Event Delegation** = Efficient event handling using bubbling

**Inefficient:**
```js
// ‚ùå Multiple listeners
doc.querySelector('.item1').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
doc.querySelector('.item2').addEventListener('click', handleClick);
```

**Efficient delegation:**
```js
// ‚úÖ Single parent listener
doc.querySelector('.list').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  if (e.target.classList.contains('item')) {
    console.log(`Clicked: ${e.target.textContent}`);
  }
});
```

**Benefits:**
- Works with dynamic elements
- Better performance
- Less memory usage

**localStorage** = Browser persistent storage

**Basic operations:**
```js
// Store
localStorage.setItem('key', 'value');

// Retrieve
const value = localStorage.getItem('key');

// Remove
localStorage.removeItem('key');

// Clear all
localStorage.clear();
```

**Objects/Arrays:**
```js
// Store object
localStorage.setItem('user', JSON.stringify(user));

// Retrieve object
const user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('user'));
```

**Key points:**
- Persists after browser restart
- ~5MB limit per domain
- Stores only strings
- Use JSON for complex data
- Avoid sensitive info (passwords, tokens)

**Object Iteration Methods** = Convert object data to arrays

```js
const user = { name: "Chuks", age: 21, country: "Nigeria" };

Object.keys(user)    // ["name", "age", "country"] - property names
Object.values(user)  // ["Chuks", 21, "Nigeria"] - property values  
Object.entries(user) // [["name", "Chuks"], ["age", 21], ...] - key-value pairs
```

**Common Patterns:**
```js
// Loop through object
Object.entries(user).forEach(([key, value]) => {
  console.log(`${key}: ${value}`);
});

// Convert back to object
const updated = Object.fromEntries(Object.entries(user));

// Filter object properties
const stringsOnly = Object.fromEntries(
  Object.entries(user).filter(([k, v]) => typeof v === 'string')
);
```

**Use cases:**
- **keys()** - get property names
- **values()** - work with values only  
- **entries()** - need both key + value

**encodeURIComponent()** = Encodes text for URL safety

**Converts:** `space & ?` ‚Üí `%20%20%26%20%3F`

**When to use:** URL parameters, query strings, form data

```js
// Safe URL construction
const query = "coffee & tea";
const url = `https://api.com/search?q=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`;
// ‚Üí "https://api.com/search?q=coffee%20%26%20tea"

// Without encoding - URL breaks!
const badUrl = `https://api.com/search?q=${query}`;
// ‚Üí "https://api.com/search?q=coffee & tea" (invalid)
```

**encodeURIComponent vs encodeURI:**
- **encodeURIComponent** - encodes most chars (/, ?, =, &) - use for URL parts
- **encodeURI** - preserves URL structure - use for full URLs

**Modern alternative:**
```js
const params = new URLSearchParams({ query: "coffee & tea" });
const url = `https://api.com/search?${params}`; // auto-encodes
```

**Always encode** user input before putting in URLs!

**Module Export Patterns:**

**CommonJS (Node.js default):**
```js
// Export
module.exports = functionName
module.exports = { func1, func2 }

// Import
const func = require('./file')
const { func1 } = require('./file')
```

**ES Modules:**
```json
// package.json
{ "type": "module" }
```

```js
// Export
export const func = () => {}
export default func

// Import
import func from './file.js'
import { func1 } from './file.js'
```

**Key difference:** CommonJS uses `module.exports/require`, ES uses `export/import`

